nerable to potential entry into this market.  The acquisition by SCHS of PD, its largest customer, is, we have found, a mechanism for shoring up its dominance of the upstream market by raising barriers to entry in that market.  By the same token, SCHS\'92s im
perative to defend its dominance in the upstream market provides the incentive for anti-competitive behaviour in the downstream market and the transaction provides the means for pursuing that conduct.{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s14{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ql\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch{\*\cs23\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up8\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 Although at opposite ends of the technology spectrum, this is remarkably similar to the conclusion of the US Appeals Court in its much quoted recent decision in the Microsoft case: \'93Microsoft\'92s efforts to gain market share in one market (browsers) served 
