est that PD has already engaged in this practice.  A counter-argument, and one that is borne out by the allegation that predation has already occurred, is that the transaction does not enhance PD\'92s ability to predate \'96 its ability to predate was given by i
ts pre-merger market power and this has not increased in consequence of the merger.  However, there is little question that the ability to predate is substantially enhanced by the deep pockets of a powerful shareholder, particularly one that may be willing
 to take significant losses downstream in order to defend its dominance in an important upstream market.{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s14{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ql\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch{\*\cs23\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up8\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 The parties have insisted that they have not been found guilty of restrictive practices in the past and that we cannot make our decision on the basis of an inference of future conduct.  We cannot, it is insisted, engage in speculation about the future; we
 must rather concern ourselves with evidence from the present.  We do not understand this argument.  Merger regulation is, in significant part, inherently speculative - it is pre-emptive insofar as it designed to ensure that the merger proposed does not gi
ve rise to a market structure that lends itself to restrictive practices.  It is our view that the market structure that will emerge from this transaction does lend itself to a number of restrictive practices, including predation, not all of which can be f
orestalled by the imposition of conditions.  }}}
