\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\f4\lang1033\f4\fs24\f4\lang1025\qj 58.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls0\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang1033\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 Section 12A(2)(g) of the Act enjoins us to consider \'93whether the business of part of the business of a party to the merger or proposed merger has failed or is likely to fail.\'94  The parties have raised the failing firm defense.{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s14{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ql\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch{\*\cs23\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up8\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 Anti-trust jurisdictions differ in the way in which they treat the failing firm defence. The concept originated in the United States where it provides an absolute defense to a finding that a merger will substantially lessen competition. It was first recog
nized in {\ul\ulc0 International Shoe Co. v. FTC, 280 U.S. 291 (1930}). Because it provides an absolute defence its requirements are rigorous and difficult to meet. Also see the 1992 US Merger Guidelines. The EU in {\ul\ulc0 Kali-Salz/MdK/Treuhand, Case IV/M308 [1994] 0.J. L18
6} has broadly followed {\ul\ulc0 United States v. General Dynamics Corp., 415 U.S. 486 (1974}) in dealing with{\ul\ulc0  }the failing firm defence. With regard to Canadian merger law Paul S. Crampton in his book {\ul\ulc0\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\i\loch\i Mergers and the Competition Act}, 1990 in footnote 59a on p.408 quo
tes the Competition Authority in the Wadair/PWA merger indicating that \'93In assessing the failing firm factor in mergers that are otherwise considered to be substantially anti-competitive, the Director requires information relating to two issues: 1) the ext
ent to which failure is, in fact likely to occur; and 2) whether there are alternatives to the merger that would be less restrictive of competition.\'94   }}}
{\*\cs23\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up10\rtlch\af6\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f1\fs24\lang7177\loch\f1\fs24\lang7177 } In effect, they argue, as th
ey are entitled to do, that the prospective failure of PD, the target firm, justifies the application of a lower anti-trust standard to this transaction. The merger, they claim, is necessary to ensure PD\'92s continued presence in the market. Absent the merge
r, PD will fail. In that event, a significant competitor will have been removed from the market - competition will have been diminished in consequence of the failure of this competitor, more particularly if the productive capacity represented by PD\'92s mater
ial assets exits the market altogether.  Under these circumstances \'96 that is, if the firm (and, more so, its assets) exits the market - competition will actually have diminished thus exerting upward pressure on candle prices.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang1033\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\f4\lang1033\f4\fs24\f4\lang1025\qj 59.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls0\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang1033\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 We should, at the outset, indicate a plausible alternative scenario in the event of PD\'92s demise. There is, it is common cause, considerable excess capacity \'96 40% is the figure given \'96 in this industry.  Moreover it is common cause that that there is relati
ve ease of entry into candle manufacturing, the downstream market.  It is, in our view, eminently plausible that, upon PD\'92s exit, its existing competitors will, through utilizing their spare capacity, increase their output and compete for a share of PD\'92s e
rstwhile market.  Equally, new firms may enter the market, possibly availing themselves of those of PD\'92s material assets that come onto the market.  Indeed SCHS itself has insisted that it will enter the market should PD fail.{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s14{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ql\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch{\*\cs23\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up8\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 SCHS suggests that the fact that it will enter the market should PD fail is further evidence that prohibiting the transaction will make no difference to the competitive structure of the market.  Regardless of whether the transaction is approved or prohibi
ted, we will have a vertically integrated firm participating in the market.  We do not accept this argument.  SCHS is, of course, perfectly entitled to vertically integrate through internal growth because in order to do so it will have to {\ul\ulc0 compete} for its s
hare of the downstream market in much the same way as a firm is entitled to expand horizontally, even to monopoly, as long as it achieves this by competing.  Merger regulation is meant to prevent the attainment of an anti-competitive position through means
 other than competition. }}}
{\*\cs23\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up10\rtlch\af6\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f1\fs24\lang7177\loch\f1\fs24\lang7177 }  On this scenario competitio
n will actually intensify in the wake of PD\'92s failure.  Moreover, the relative resilience of PD\'92s competitors will have been rewarded by the market share that they will gain as a result of the very process of competition.  }
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang1033\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\f4\lang1033\f4\fs24\f4\lang1025\qj 60.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls0\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang1033\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 However, the \'91failing firm\'92 is a term of art in merger regulation and it is incumbent upon us to examine the criteria commonly used in assessing the salience of the failing firm defence in this case.  We do however insist that, as in most anti-trust assess
ments, the facts of the specific case will take precedence over the application of a derived formula.  In our view the existence of considerable excess capacity is a salient fact that militates against the prospect of a shortfall in supply, and therefore u
pward pressure on price, in the wake of failure.{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s14{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ql\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch{\*\cs23\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up8\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 The parties have acknowledged this argument but insist that this will only take place with a considerable time lag \'96 eighteen months was suggested.  During the intervening period there will be a shortfall in demand.   However with a large proportion of un
utilised capacity already in place and relative ease of entry, we cannot understand why there should be such a slow response in a situation of excess demand.}}}
{\*\cs23\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up10\rtlch\af6\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f1\fs24\lang7177\loch\f1\fs24\lang7177 }  We nevertheless will reflect on the range of tests and criteria conventionally employed to assess the impact of potential firm failure on the competition implications of a merger.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang1033\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\f4\lang1033\f4\fs24\f4\lang1025\qj 61.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls0\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang1033\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 First, is PD failing?  According to the parties: \'93 PD is demonstrably insolvent\'94. {\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s14{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ql\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch{\*\cs23\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up8\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 This is substantiated by evidence, which is claimed confidential.}}}
{\*\cs23\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up10\rtlch\af6\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af6\langfe255\hich\f1\fs24\lang7177\loch\f1\fs24\lang7177 }  }
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang1033\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\f4\lang1033\f4\fs24\f4\lang1025\qj 62.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls0\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang1033\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 There is little doubt that PD\'92s financial predicament is dire. We should note that we do not understand, nor have the parties or the commission shed any light upon, how a firm with significant market share in a mature industry has landed in this sorry situ
ation.  It has not, after all, been derailed by a new innovation to which it has not had access.  The Commission claims that the firm\'92s auditors believe that the firm sold by SCHS to the Goodman family in 1995 was already in trouble.  Others suggest that P
D has been pricing below cost, presumably cushioned by a steady supply of loan capital from SCHS.  The Goodman\'92s allege that PD has been prejudiced by SCHS failure to adhere to the terms of the supply agreement.  SCHS implies that management failure accoun
ts for the firm\'92s predicament.  }
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang1033\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\f4\lang1033\f4\fs24\f4\lang1025\qj 63.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls0\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang1033\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 None of these various allegations and explanations has been satisfactorily supported by evidence.  However, an understanding of the causes of PD\'92s failure is pertinent for two reasons: In the first place, it is not clear how SCHS intends post merger to add
ress the cause of PD\'92s possible failure and, as we shall demonstrate below, this has bearing on the merger evaluation, particularly on the question of countervailing efficiency gains resulting from the transaction as well as its impact on public interest. 
 Moreover, failure, if it is to occur, will happen at the behest of SCHS, immeasurably the largest creditor.  It appears that PD\'92s failure could have been triggered by SCHS at any time over the last several years. }
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang1033\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\f4\lang1033\f4\fs24\f4\lang1025\qj 64.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls0\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang1033\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 Unless we understand why the firm has been unable to survive profitably, it is difficult to understand why SCHS should trigger liquidation now rather than 12 months ago or, indeed, rather than 12 months hence.  One possible inference is that SCHS has chose
n to subsidise a captive, though inefficient, customer in preference to instability (read, competition) in the market for its candle wax.  If this is so then SCHS has reaped the consequences that protection so often begets: increasing inefficiency matched 
by increasing subsidy.  It should not expect the competition authorities to rescue it by sanctioning the ultimate protective umbrella, namely full vertical integration, regardless of the impact on competition.  In short, while we believe that PD is in dire
 straits, we are not certain whether its failure is necessarily imminent \'96 that will depend upon SCHS\'92s continued interest in protecting the company.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang1033\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\f4\lang1033\f4\fs24\f4\lang1025\qj 65.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls0\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang1033\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 Secondly, has there been any attempt to find an alternative suitor for PD, one that raises fewer competition concerns than SCHS?  SCHS makes the plausible argument that few buyers would be willing to assume PD\'92s massive debt.  However it appears that there
 has been a concerted attempt to find a buyer for PD.  Note that this search has specifically excluded other South African candle manufacturers.  SCHS avers that they have been excluded in part because it was calculated that a horizontal transaction would 
not have received competition approval.  SCHS has also made it emphatically clear that it would not welcome a situation where it was beholden to a single large customer.   The absence or presence of willing buyers is, for the most part, a function of price
 \'96 this is after all not a new untested product; its market and mode of distribution is well known and relatively predictable.  The price of PD is largely a derivative of the extent to which SCHS is willing to assume the target company\'92s debt. SCHS is prop
osing to purchase PD for a nominal sum because it has effectively been willing to write off its massive debt in exchange for vertical integration. Should it be willing to do the same in respect of other purchasers then alternative offers may come to the fo
re.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang1033\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\f4\lang1033\f4\fs24\f4\lang1025\qj 66.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls0\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang1033\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 Thirdly, is there any prospect of re-organising PD?  That is, is there any prospect of PD surviving without the merger?  As we shall elaborate when we discuss the prospect of countervailing efficiency gains, little has been said about the prospects of rais
ing PD\'92s performance.  We are accordingly unable to answer this question.  SCHS, though revealing few details, believes that it is capable of turning around PD.  It is not clear why it cannot achieve this without first merging.  SCHS has argued that it has
 been in effective control of PD since 1998 \'96 if it is possible to restore PD\'92s fortunes through the adoption of pro-competitive strategies then surely SCHS should be able to achieve this from its present position without resorting to the expedient of an a
nti-competitive merger.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang1033\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\f4\lang1033\f4\fs24\f4\lang1025\qj 67.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls0\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang1033\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 Fourthly, what will happen to PD\'92s market share?  The Commission errs by asking where PD\'92s market share will go {\ul\ulc0 post-merger}.  Clearly, it will go to the acquiring firm, SCHS, or, technically, it will remain with PD now controlled by SCHS.  However, what is
 pertinent is what will happen to its market share {\ul\ulc0 post-failure}?  If it can be shown that the acquiring firm (SCHS) will simply mop up the target firms (PD\'92s) market share post-failure then there is, it is argued, little point in prohibiting the merger bec
ause the impact on market shares in the downstream market will be identical \'96 either way, the acquiring firm will take the target\'92s market share.  However as we have demonstrated above the post-failure outcome is by no means clear because there will be sev
eral competitors contending for PD\'92s market share including existing participants in the candle market and possibly new entrants, including SCHS itself.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang1033\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\f4\lang1033\f4\fs24\f4\lang1025\qj 68.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls0\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang1033\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 Finally, what will become of PD\'92s assets post failure?  We have already suggested that the pertinence of this question is eroded by the existence of significant over-capacity.  On the evidence the most likely outcome is that certain of the assets, to the e
xtent that they are divisible, will be acquired by new entrants, while others may find their way out of the country.  However, in the context of considerable excess capacity we do not believe that the market will be characterized by a significant supply sh
ortfall post-failure.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang1033\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\f4\lang1033\f4\fs24\f4\lang1025\qj 69.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls0\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang1033\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 In summary, we find that the failing firm defence does not support approval of this transaction.  First, it is not clear that the firm will actually fail despite its parlous circumstances. Secondly, the extent of excess capacity in the industry and ease of
 entry suggests that the competitive situation will not deteriorate in consequence of the exit of PD (or its assets) \'96 quite the contrary, we are likely to see an intensification in competition. Third, if SCHS has a pro-competitive strategy for reviving PD
\'92s fortunes it is not clear why this cannot be pursued through means other than the merger.  Finally, while we are persuaded that SCHS and PD have sought alternative purchasers, the success of their search will, in a relatively stable industry, depend on p
rice and that, in turn, will depend on the quantum of PD\'92s debt that SCHS is willing to assume \'96 it is the only purchaser because it has only been willing to write off its own debt in exchange for complete vertical integration.{\*\cs23\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up10\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\f1\fs24\lang7177\loch\f1\fs24\lang7177  {\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s14{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ql\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch{\*\cs23\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up8\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs20\lang1033\i0\b0 Expressed conversely, through writing off its debt (that is, through assuming PD\'92s debt) SCHS has effectively demonstrated its willingness to pay a premium price for PD \'96 the inference is that it is willing to pay this price because, through vertical inte
gration, it secures dominance of the markets in question.  Other purchasers would not be willing to pay this price \'96 or, assume this level of debt \'96 because they would not be able to reap the anti-competitive benefits of vertical integration.  However, at 
a more realistic price, one that reflected simply the cost of acquiring a significant candle manufacturer, alternative purchasers may well be available.}}}
}}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang1033\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033 
\par \pard\plain \li360\ri0\lin360\rin0\fi0\keepn\f4\lang1033\i\b\f4\fs24\i\b\f4\lang1025\i\b\qj \ltrpar\s13\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\li360\ri0\lin360\rin0\fi0\keepn\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ai\ab\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang1033\i\b\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033\i\b {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033\i\b Pro-competitive Efficiency Gains}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang1033\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\f4\lang1033\f4\fs24\f4\lang1025\qj 70.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls0\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang1033\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 Are the anti-competitive consequences of the transaction countervailed by pro-competitive efficiency gains?}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang1033\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\f4\lang1033\f4\fs24\f4\lang1025\qj 71.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls0\li720\ri0\lin720\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af4\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af4\langfe255\hich\f4\fs24\lang1033\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f4\fs24\lang1033\i0\b0 The Commission points out that SCHS has not specified efficiency gains arising from the transaction aside, that is, from a blanket assertion that these are assured by the injection of SCHS\'92s superior management and financial resources.  We have already poi
